git replace --graft <TARGET_COMMIT_HASH> <EXISTING_PARENT_HASH> <ADDITIONAL_PARENT_HASH> to chnage parent of a commit.
git reset --hard HEAD~1 is set to deleate the present HEAD, idk how true, there is also a --soft option which idk how to use for now.
git status shows all the chnages made with respect to HEAD.
git commit -m 'bla' = git update-ref refs/heads/master $(echo 'bla' | git commit-tree -p HEAD $(git write-tree))
-S for commit-tree and commit will sign the commit cryptographically!
git log --show-signature to verify signature.
git config user.signingkey to verify the signing key, it should be a keyid string(all caps): FF2DF70EB208A53A52D77140EF585FDD26A0DD75
'git reflog expire --expire-unreachable=now --all; git gc --prune=now' to deleate dangling trees
`````
                    ┌─ W ── X ── Y ── Z   [Branch Z]
                    │
  A (Common Root) ──┤
  [D~3]             │
                    └─ B ── C ── D* [Branch D (HEAD)]
                      [D~2] [D^] [D]
$ git show-branch
! [Z] Z
* [D] D
--
* [D] D
* [D^] C
* [D~2] B
+ [Z] Z
+ [Z^] Y
+ [Z~2] X
+ [Z~3] W
+* [D~3] A
``````
Reflog is like a trash bin that stores deleted objects for 30 days for kinda fail-safe. Can be viewed with 'git reflog' jsut like git log
'git stash' stashes ur chnages to the stash so u can call it a day and restart tommorrow without making a useless commit. git stash will stash away the current working tree and the index. U do 'git stash list' 'git reflog show stash' and 'git stash apply' the next day. But if u wrote somewhere that u stashed the changes, then technically u made changes and must revert the changes with 'git reset --hard HEAD' before being able to apply 'git stash apply' unless ur really good at jsut reverting the changes urself.
The stash is technically stored as a commit but not perminatly.
'git stash clear' will clear the stash.

'git push -u origin main' is used when the first branch-main in this case us pushed-'git remote add origin url' is used to add origin, syncing the next changes is simple as 'git push' to sync changes local to serverand 'git pull' to sync server to local.
Anyways not the repo is in git@github.com:aur4or4a/Git_Practice.git.
'git brach -M main' will change current brach name to 'main'.
